    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-09-18T21:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-09-18T21:00:00-05:00" n="350"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d350">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">715.1715/390: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Honduras</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Lay</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tegucigalpa</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-09-18T20:00:00-06:00"
                            >September 18, 1930—8 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received September 19—12:50 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>87. The following telegram was sent to the Legation at Managua: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“September 18, 8 p.m. Referring to your telegram of September 16, 2
                                p.m.,<note n="97" xml:id="d350fn97">See telegram No. 115 of the same
                                date to the Secretary of State, <hi rend="italic">supra.</hi>
                            </note> stating that full text of the boundary protocol, proposed by the
                            Government of Honduras and transmitted with my air mail letter of August
                            17, is accepted by the Government of Nicaragua with the omission of
                            article 5. I take great pleasure in informing you that after explaining
                            to the President that the omission of article 5 would improve chances of
                            ratification in the Nicaraguan Congress he agreed to this text of the
                            protocol in full without article 5.</p>
                        <p>Believing the moment opportune and for reasons you mention, I urged him
                            to reconsider his previous objection to signing in Managua. A copy of a
                            note from the Honduranean Foreign Office to this Legation agreeing to
                            text of protocol in full with omission of article 5 and stating that
                            Honduranean Government would have no objection to signing in Managua
                            will be sent you by marine air mail tomorrow”.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lay</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
